  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This Dryad dataset, deposited in 2017 by an international team led from the University of British Columbia, underpins phylogenomic and genomic analyses of novel holozoan predators that reshaped understanding of early animal evolution. With 718 views and 147 downloads recorded through DataCite, the resource has attracted steady community access, and formal data citations confirm its reuse in at least one subsequent peer-reviewed study in <em>eLife</em> as recently as 2025.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset supports a collaboration spanning four institutions across Canada, Russia, and the Czech Republic \u2014 including the University of British Columbia, the Russian Academy of Sciences, the Czech Academy of Sciences, and Penza State University. The seven contributors brought together expertise in microbial ecology, protistology, phylogenetics, and comparative genomics to characterize newly described unicellular predators positioned near the base of Holozoa, the clade that encompasses animals and their closest microbial relatives. By providing the underlying sequence alignments, phylogenetic trees, and gene repertoire data, the dataset makes the core analytical evidence for the companion article fully reproducible and independently verifiable.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">The scientific significance of the work centers on two intertwined findings: a revised holozoan phylogeny that accommodates previously uncharacterized lineages, and evidence that a two-component signalling system \u2014 long considered a hallmark of bacterial regulation \u2014 was present in the last common ancestor of animals. These conclusions bear directly on long-standing questions about how multicellularity and cell-to-cell communication evolved. The dataset's conceptual scope, spanning phylogenetics, transcription factor repertoires, and ancestral genome reconstruction, positions it as a reference point for researchers probing the deep evolutionary origins of animal complexity.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Downstream reuse, though still modest in formal citation counts, is substantive in character. A 2025 <em>eLife</em> article on G-protein-coupled receptor diversity in the closest living relatives of metazoa, authored by researchers at the University of California, Berkeley and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute, drew on this dataset \u2014 indicating that its value extends into active, well-resourced research programmes on pre-metazoan cell signalling. This thematic continuity, from two-component systems to GPCR evolution, suggests the dataset is being incorporated into a growing comparative framework for reconstructing ancestral animal biology. The dataset also carries a connection to SDG 14 (Life below water), reflecting the aquatic microbiological contexts in which these novel predators were isolated and studied.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Stewardship is robust: the dataset is openly accessible through Dryad, a re3data-registered repository that issues DOI-based persistent identifiers and maintains open access as its default policy. The deposit is structured across multiple individually citable Dryad records, facilitating granular reuse of specific data components. Collectively, the usage metrics, the cross-institutional provenance of the original team, and the appearance of formal data citations nearly eight years after deposition indicate that this resource continues to serve as a durable, reusable foundation for comparative evolutionary genomics at the animal-microbe boundary.</p>",
